1
00:00:17,916 --> 00:00:20,541
[NARRATOR] SEVEN-O's got some
new gadgets, friends!

2
00:00:20,625 --> 00:00:22,083
Number one!

3
00:00:22,166 --> 00:00:23,541
With these, you can speed down

4
00:00:23,625 --> 00:00:25,666
even the most narrow,
cluttered roads!

5
00:00:25,750 --> 00:00:27,875
Jet roller skates!


6
00:00:27,958 --> 00:00:29,166
Number two!

7
00:00:29,250 --> 00:00:31,125
Equipped with powerful rockets,

8
00:00:31,208 --> 00:00:33,208
it's sure to come in handy
at some point!

9
00:00:33,291 --> 00:00:34,750
Jet pack!


10
00:00:34,833 --> 00:00:36,500
Number three!

11
00:00:36,583 --> 00:00:38,166
Wanna see what
your partner sees?

12
00:00:38,250 --> 00:00:39,541
Now you can!

13
00:00:39,625 --> 00:00:42,666
New function. View Jack!


14
00:00:43,000 --> 00:00:44,333
[NARRATOR]
That last one?

15
00:00:44,416 --> 00:00:47,375
It's right out of every
adolescent boy's wildest dreams.

16
00:00:47,458 --> 00:00:48,875
Sick new items, man!

17
00:00:48,958 --> 00:00:51,291
Those are all super badass!
Go, Apple!

18
00:00:51,375 --> 00:00:54,541
[laughs] Thanks, but I insist
you call me, "Doctor."

19
00:00:54,625 --> 00:00:56,041
Really nice work, Apple!

20
00:00:56,125 --> 00:00:58,500
[APPLE laughs]
What'd I just say?

21
00:00:58,583 --> 00:01:00,166
You might win a science
fair with these,

22
00:01:00,250 --> 00:01:01,250
but none of 'em will help us

23
00:01:01,333 --> 00:01:03,000
to solve a damn thing,
Apple Bieber.

24
00:01:03,083 --> 00:01:04,250
It's "Doctor"!

25
00:01:04,333 --> 00:01:06,625
So, can we talk about
this weird new function

26
00:01:06,708 --> 00:01:08,000
you put into the eye system?

27
00:01:08,083 --> 00:01:09,250
It's called the view jack.

28
00:01:09,333 --> 00:01:10,625
Sure, that.

29
00:01:10,708 --> 00:01:12,583
You could use it to spy
on us while we're changing.

30
00:01:12,666 --> 00:01:13,875
[APPLE gasps]

31
00:01:13,958 --> 00:01:14,750
Uh...

32
00:01:14,833 --> 00:01:16,000
[KAY gasps]

33
00:01:17,166 --> 00:01:18,625
No, I would never!

34
00:01:18,708 --> 00:01:20,166
You've got it all wrong here!

35
00:01:20,250 --> 00:01:22,500
Its primary function
is sharing information,

36
00:01:22,583 --> 00:01:23,916
particularly on
Overdrive targets.

37
00:01:24,000 --> 00:01:24,958
[DEANA]
Aw, hell, no!

38
00:01:25,041 --> 00:01:26,750
Okay, fine.
I'll adjust it, then!

39
00:01:26,833 --> 00:01:29,166
I said hell no, Apple.

40
00:01:29,250 --> 00:01:31,291
Doug! Help me out, please!

41
00:01:31,375 --> 00:01:33,583
[DOUG] I mean, this stuff
is cool, and all,

42
00:01:33,666 --> 00:01:35,708
but I do see the
ladies' point here.

43
00:01:35,791 --> 00:01:39,000
Plus, it's hard to say
if we'd use any of this.

44
00:01:39,083 --> 00:01:39,958
[APPLE groans]

45
00:01:40,041 --> 00:01:41,291
[NARRATOR]
That's right!

46
00:01:41,375 --> 00:01:43,166
This is just your typical,
run-of-the-mill cop show

47
00:01:43,250 --> 00:01:45,333
about good detectives
haunting a beat, so.


48
00:01:45,416 --> 00:01:47,375
If you want cool tech,
you'd better look elsewhere!

49
00:01:47,458 --> 00:01:49,250
Hey. Twavis says
he needs you all

50
00:01:49,333 --> 00:01:50,958
to come see him, quick.

51
00:01:51,041 --> 00:01:51,833
[GROUP]
Hm?

52
00:01:51,916 --> 00:01:54,208
Something about a kidnapping.

53
00:01:54,291 --> 00:01:57,208
[NARRATOR]
Yes, she did just say, "Twavis!"

54
00:03:29,666 --> 00:03:32,333
[TRAVIS] This victim is a young
woman named Sarah Dorman.

55
00:03:32,416 --> 00:03:35,791
The daughter of William Dorman,
the leading mayoral candidate.

56
00:03:35,875 --> 00:03:38,666
That is unfortunate, but what's
it got to do with us?

57
00:03:38,750 --> 00:03:41,916
Yeah. Kidnapping cases are
outside our jurisdiction.

58
00:03:42,000 --> 00:03:42,958
[door creaks]

59
00:03:43,041 --> 00:03:45,541
[COOPER]
Indeed, allow me to explain.

60
00:03:53,958 --> 00:03:55,541
Whoa! Who's that?

61
00:03:55,625 --> 00:03:58,375
You seriously don't know?
What a dumbass!

62
00:03:58,458 --> 00:03:59,958
This is Brian Cooper.

63
00:04:00,041 --> 00:04:01,666
Our Military Secretary.

64
00:04:01,750 --> 00:04:02,750
[KIRILL gasps]

65
00:04:02,833 --> 00:04:04,333
[NARRATOR]
Yep. You folks are smart,

66
00:04:04,416 --> 00:04:05,625
so I'm sure you remember that,

67
00:04:05,708 --> 00:04:08,125
despite being a police
organization first,

68
00:04:08,208 --> 00:04:11,041
SEVEN-O is also under
military jurisdiction!

69
00:04:11,125 --> 00:04:12,666
[COOPER]
The criminals gave us a clue

70
00:04:12,750 --> 00:04:14,666
when they sent us
their ransom demand.

71
00:04:14,750 --> 00:04:16,833
They identified themselves
as Esperanza.

72
00:04:16,916 --> 00:04:17,916
[KIRILL gasping]

73
00:04:22,166 --> 00:04:23,250
[DOUG]
"Ransom demand"?

74
00:04:23,333 --> 00:04:25,041
So, that means this
is just a cash grab.

75
00:04:25,125 --> 00:04:27,250
[COOPER] Your assessment
is likely correct.

76
00:04:27,333 --> 00:04:29,500
But, in light of the upcoming
mayoral elections,

77
00:04:29,583 --> 00:04:32,625
we need to be open to the idea
that Dorman's political rivals

78
00:04:32,708 --> 00:04:34,041
could also be involved.

79
00:04:34,125 --> 00:04:35,875
And, considering the fact that
we're going up against

80
00:04:35,958 --> 00:04:39,000
Esperanza, we can't
afford to take chances.

81
00:04:39,083 --> 00:04:41,166
We've got to be ready
for anything.

82
00:04:46,875 --> 00:04:48,083
[DOUG]
Understood, sir.

83
00:04:48,166 --> 00:04:49,666
So, we should treat this
as a direct case, then?

84
00:04:49,750 --> 00:04:51,250
[KIRILL]
Hey, what's a direct case?

85
00:04:51,333 --> 00:04:52,375
[KAY]
It's the term for a case

86
00:04:52,458 --> 00:04:53,916
that comes directly
from the military.

87
00:04:54,000 --> 00:04:56,500
[COOPER] Yes, but there's
a bit more to this one.

88
00:04:56,583 --> 00:04:58,291
[TRAVIS]
What else should we know?

89
00:04:58,375 --> 00:05:00,250
Please save my daughter,
I beg you!

90
00:05:00,333 --> 00:05:02,208
Save my dear Sarah! Please!

91
00:05:02,291 --> 00:05:04,833
I don't even care if the media
says I'm weak for negotiating

92
00:05:04,916 --> 00:05:08,333
with kidnappers! Let them!
Just save her!

93
00:05:08,416 --> 00:05:10,000
[COOPER]
And Dorman, well...

94
00:05:10,083 --> 00:05:12,166
He's an old friend
of the family.

95
00:05:12,250 --> 00:05:14,250
[DOUG]
Say no more, sir. We're on it.

96
00:05:14,333 --> 00:05:16,791
So, is there a plan
in place yet?

97
00:05:16,875 --> 00:05:19,625
[TRAVIS] There's a great deal
more risk involved than usual.

98
00:05:19,708 --> 00:05:23,000
Mister Dorman has insisted upon
handing over the ransom himself.

99
00:05:23,083 --> 00:05:24,833
You'll be nearby, surveying.

100
00:05:24,916 --> 00:05:27,250
And, in the event that
things don't go as planned,

101
00:05:27,333 --> 00:05:29,500
you'll be there for backup.

102
00:05:29,583 --> 00:05:31,291
Doug, you're the team leader.

103
00:05:31,375 --> 00:05:33,791
Mr. Dorman will be
wearing a radio,

104
00:05:33,875 --> 00:05:37,291
but for security reasons, he
won't have his own receiver.

105
00:05:37,375 --> 00:05:40,750
Your priority here is the
victim's safety, above all else.

106
00:05:40,833 --> 00:05:42,958
And don't worry about
apprehending the suspects.

107
00:05:43,041 --> 00:05:44,083
[phone rings]

108
00:05:45,583 --> 00:05:48,041
There he goes. Doug? Follow?

109
00:05:48,125 --> 00:05:49,875
[DOUG]
Yeah. Be careful, you two.

110
00:05:49,958 --> 00:05:51,000
[siren blares]

111
00:05:51,083 --> 00:05:52,083
[KIRILL gasps]

112
00:05:54,500 --> 00:05:57,458
[KAY] He's headed
towards the river now.

113
00:05:57,541 --> 00:05:58,458
[DEANA]
Well, shit.

114
00:05:58,541 --> 00:06:00,208
What's the matter?

115
00:06:00,291 --> 00:06:01,583
[DEANA]
There's a fire.

116
00:06:01,666 --> 00:06:03,750
[sirens blare]

117
00:06:04,333 --> 00:06:05,750
[KIRILL growls]

118
00:06:08,583 --> 00:06:10,458
Dammit. Problem here, too.

119
00:06:10,541 --> 00:06:12,125
We'll have to take
the long way around.

120
00:06:12,208 --> 00:06:15,291
[DOUG]
Roger that. I'll tail him alone.

121
00:06:25,750 --> 00:06:27,833
[DEANA]
Damn! I lost my view.

122
00:06:27,916 --> 00:06:30,750
Not good. They found
the transmitter.

123
00:06:30,833 --> 00:06:31,875
[ALL gasp]

124
00:06:33,250 --> 00:06:35,416
[DOUG] It's looking bad.
They're onto us, no doubt.

125
00:06:35,500 --> 00:06:37,750
I'm gonna have to handle
this one by myself!

126
00:06:37,833 --> 00:06:40,041
[DORMAN] You give me back
my daughter, now!

127
00:06:40,125 --> 00:06:41,958
[THUG 09B groans]

128
00:06:42,041 --> 00:06:43,500
[THUG 09A groans]

129
00:06:43,583 --> 00:06:45,041
Are you okay, sir?

130
00:06:51,083 --> 00:06:53,916
[DEANA]
Hey, where did they go?

131
00:06:54,000 --> 00:06:55,291
[BOTH gasp]

132
00:06:55,375 --> 00:06:58,875
Understood. I'll ask for
a cordon on the main roads.

133
00:06:58,958 --> 00:07:01,250
Let's hope they're not
out of the ward yet.

134
00:07:01,333 --> 00:07:03,333
Target is confirmed
on the run...

135
00:07:03,416 --> 00:07:05,708
Do you suspect that
the fire was arson?

136
00:07:05,791 --> 00:07:08,958
Yes. An attempt to sabotage
our investigation.

137
00:07:09,041 --> 00:07:10,500
A clever one, too.

138
00:07:10,583 --> 00:07:13,583
They knew firefighters would
need to gather near the river.

139
00:07:13,666 --> 00:07:15,875
[DORMAN] Hey, this wasn't
part of the deal!

140
00:07:15,958 --> 00:07:18,541
SEVEN-O was supposed to
botch the investigation.

141
00:07:18,625 --> 00:07:20,041
Then I'd look like a hero

142
00:07:20,125 --> 00:07:22,125
when I rescued my
daughter all by myself!

143
00:07:22,208 --> 00:07:24,250
It was the plan
we all agreed upon!

144
00:07:24,333 --> 00:07:26,416
That way, I'd be sure to win
the election and the current

145
00:07:26,500 --> 00:07:28,541
mayor's drug policies
would go out the window.

146
00:07:28,625 --> 00:07:30,666
It was win-win!
So, what'd I miss?

147
00:07:30,750 --> 00:07:32,000
[ZABEL]
The plan changed.

148
00:07:32,083 --> 00:07:34,500
We have a higher priority
to address now.

149
00:07:34,583 --> 00:07:36,500
[DORMAN]
Who are you? I don't like this.

150
00:07:36,583 --> 00:07:37,750
[ZABEL]
I have a little message for you

151
00:07:37,833 --> 00:07:39,000
to pass along to your friends.

152
00:07:39,083 --> 00:07:40,333
I don't know who you are,

153
00:07:40,416 --> 00:07:42,916
but no part of the plan
included kidnapping a cop!

154
00:07:43,000 --> 00:07:44,458
Cooper's a family friend!

155
00:07:44,541 --> 00:07:45,916
What the hell are we
supposed to do

156
00:07:46,000 --> 00:07:47,958
if something happens
to the officer, huh?

157
00:07:48,041 --> 00:07:49,625
[ZABEL]
Heh.

158
00:07:49,708 --> 00:07:51,750
Oh, no. Did you kill him?

159
00:07:51,833 --> 00:07:53,625
[DORMAN groans]

160
00:07:53,708 --> 00:07:56,500
[ZABEL] I'm afraid the matter
is none of your business.

161
00:07:56,583 --> 00:07:59,541
Sorry. You will keep
your promise, though.

162
00:07:59,625 --> 00:08:04,083
You're going to do everything we
tell you to, with no exceptions.

163
00:08:04,166 --> 00:08:06,000
We're in this together now.

164
00:08:06,083 --> 00:08:08,958
Even if you wanted out,
there's no turning back.

165
00:08:09,041 --> 00:08:10,750
But, is my daughter safe?

166
00:08:10,833 --> 00:08:13,291
[ZABEL] I'll release her without
a scratch, as promised.

167
00:08:13,375 --> 00:08:15,250
The boss decided in
the pen that he wouldn't

168
00:08:15,333 --> 00:08:17,791
be killin' kids no more.
Good news for you.

169
00:08:17,875 --> 00:08:20,458
[THUG 09A] Yeah, but the bad
news is he shows no mercy

170
00:08:20,541 --> 00:08:23,041
to people who waste
perfectly good food.

171
00:08:23,125 --> 00:08:25,291
Daddy fought bravely
to rescue his poor,

172
00:08:25,375 --> 00:08:27,375
innocent daughter
from the bad guys.

173
00:08:27,458 --> 00:08:30,333
That's the story you want
the papers to run, right?

174
00:08:35,208 --> 00:08:37,875
[APPLE sighs]
Just like I thought, no luck.

175
00:08:37,958 --> 00:08:40,416
These cameras are positioned
to monitor the river.

176
00:08:40,500 --> 00:08:41,791
Can't expect much.

177
00:08:41,875 --> 00:08:43,666
Can we check any
of the other feeds?

178
00:08:43,750 --> 00:08:45,500
They're in a stolen vehicle.

179
00:08:45,583 --> 00:08:48,708
The license plates aren't
gonna tell us a damn thing.

180
00:08:48,791 --> 00:08:51,083
Poor Doug.
If he doesn't make it...

181
00:08:51,166 --> 00:08:53,125
Don't even think that!

182
00:08:55,625 --> 00:08:57,416
Buzz-Cut. You can't just leave.

183
00:08:57,500 --> 00:08:59,083
That's right, we're on standby.

184
00:08:59,166 --> 00:09:00,375
Kirill!

185
00:09:02,750 --> 00:09:04,000
Dammit, Doug!

186
00:09:04,083 --> 00:09:07,375
I'm the one who's supposed
to get caught! Ya jerk!

187
00:09:07,458 --> 00:09:10,250
[DEANA] How could those lowlifes
have known about our plan?

188
00:09:10,333 --> 00:09:11,875
What the hell is going on here?

189
00:09:11,958 --> 00:09:14,000
Do you think they were
listening in on our messages?

190
00:09:14,083 --> 00:09:15,583
There's no possible way.

191
00:09:15,666 --> 00:09:18,083
I used my own personal brand
of encryption on them.

192
00:09:18,166 --> 00:09:19,666
It's pretty much infallible.

193
00:09:19,750 --> 00:09:21,708
Maybe your ego
is to blame, then.

194
00:09:21,791 --> 00:09:23,791
What if you're wrong, and
they broke the encryption?

195
00:09:23,875 --> 00:09:26,916
The radio output is so low
the signal's barely detectible!

196
00:09:27,000 --> 00:09:29,083
The technology that
amplifies the receiver--

197
00:09:29,166 --> 00:09:31,791
I'm the only person
who knows how to-- Uh!

198
00:09:31,875 --> 00:09:33,125
[door opens]

199
00:09:33,208 --> 00:09:34,958
[MAXINE]
Deana. Kay. Listen.

200
00:09:35,041 --> 00:09:36,250
[beeping]

201
00:09:36,333 --> 00:09:37,875
[DEANA] Buzz-Cut, you read?
Better come back.

202
00:09:37,958 --> 00:09:39,166
We found Dorman's daughter.

203
00:09:39,250 --> 00:09:40,500
[gasps]

204
00:09:41,875 --> 00:09:42,916
[MAXINE]
When we located the victim,

205
00:09:43,000 --> 00:09:44,791
she was able to give
the exact location

206
00:09:44,875 --> 00:09:45,958
of the kidnappers' hideout.

207
00:09:46,041 --> 00:09:47,416
Dorman was found soon after,

208
00:09:47,500 --> 00:09:50,083
unconscious in a seedy
hotel room in the area.

209
00:09:50,166 --> 00:09:51,625
Did they find Doug yet?

210
00:09:51,708 --> 00:09:53,500
The room was otherwise empty.

211
00:09:53,583 --> 00:09:55,000
Nobody in there but Dorman.

212
00:09:55,083 --> 00:09:57,125
So, they're keeping
Doug somewhere else.

213
00:09:57,208 --> 00:10:00,000
All right. Are we positive
we can trust this info?

214
00:10:00,083 --> 00:10:02,166
[MAXINE]
Yes. No doubt in my mind, sir.

215
00:10:02,250 --> 00:10:04,708
The daughter gave us some
additional intel, as well.

216
00:10:04,791 --> 00:10:09,125
Something that her dad picked
up from one of the kidnappers.

217
00:10:09,208 --> 00:10:12,166
[DORMAN]
You must've been so scared.

218
00:10:12,250 --> 00:10:14,291
I'm sorry... Sarah.

219
00:10:14,375 --> 00:10:17,000
But you're strong,
you'll be fine.

220
00:10:17,083 --> 00:10:18,833
Pass along a message from me.

221
00:10:18,916 --> 00:10:22,166
Can you do that?

222
00:10:22,250 --> 00:10:25,791
"Sergeant Doug Billingham
isn't dead, yet."

223
00:10:32,500 --> 00:10:34,291
I wanted to say thank you
for all your help

224
00:10:34,375 --> 00:10:37,250
when we last met, Doug.
I would be dead

225
00:10:37,333 --> 00:10:40,541
if it weren't for you,
and I will never forget that.

226
00:10:48,083 --> 00:10:49,625
But why would they take Doug?

227
00:10:49,708 --> 00:10:51,791
If the kidnapping
was truly a ploy

228
00:10:51,875 --> 00:10:53,333
then maybe
the kidnappers' real aim

229
00:10:53,416 --> 00:10:55,041
was to take an
investigator hostage.

230
00:10:55,125 --> 00:10:55,875
[ALL gasp]

231
00:10:55,958 --> 00:10:56,791
For revenge?

232
00:10:56,875 --> 00:10:57,958
No, sir.

233
00:10:58,041 --> 00:10:59,625
As evil as they are,
they're not stupid.

234
00:10:59,708 --> 00:11:02,125
[gasps] For information?

235
00:11:02,208 --> 00:11:06,083
[COOPER] Yes. That's more
the more likely scenario.

236
00:11:06,166 --> 00:11:07,333
I get it.

237
00:11:07,416 --> 00:11:10,375
So that's what you've
been after all along?

238
00:11:10,458 --> 00:11:11,416
[splash]

239
00:11:11,500 --> 00:11:12,666
[muffled groans]

240
00:11:12,750 --> 00:11:14,375
[COOPER] We can safely
assume that Esperanza

241
00:11:14,458 --> 00:11:15,875
kidnapped one of your comrades--

242
00:11:15,958 --> 00:11:19,125
to torture him for
classified information.

243
00:11:19,208 --> 00:11:21,875
And my best guess?
They want any intelligence

244
00:11:21,958 --> 00:11:25,000
he can provide regarding
your Anti-AMS bullets.

245
00:11:25,083 --> 00:11:26,708
We already know quite a lot.

246
00:11:26,791 --> 00:11:29,583
The five Overdrive antidote
drugs, for example.

247
00:11:29,666 --> 00:11:31,916
However, we need your help
with some of the particulars,

248
00:11:32,000 --> 00:11:33,750
proper dosages and such.

249
00:11:33,833 --> 00:11:35,875
All of the drugs
are extremely potent.

250
00:11:35,958 --> 00:11:38,750
Some are even fatal in
the wrong quantities.

251
00:11:38,833 --> 00:11:40,958
So, you see the tangle
that we're in?

252
00:11:41,041 --> 00:11:43,375
We need you to tell us
the appropriate formulas,

253
00:11:43,458 --> 00:11:46,083
and the order of operations,
if you don't mind.

254
00:11:46,166 --> 00:11:48,125
And I was hoping you might
be willing to tell me how

255
00:11:48,208 --> 00:11:50,583
this lovely little
device functions?

256
00:11:50,666 --> 00:11:53,000
It's such a mystery to me.

257
00:11:53,083 --> 00:11:55,666
That sounds just like something
Esperanza would do.

258
00:11:55,750 --> 00:11:58,125
I know how to find Doug!
I've got a great idea!

259
00:11:58,208 --> 00:11:59,208
[gasps]

260
00:11:59,291 --> 00:12:00,625
Using the view jack?

261
00:12:00,708 --> 00:12:01,833
Yes.

262
00:12:01,916 --> 00:12:03,458
I made a modification
to the radio program

263
00:12:03,541 --> 00:12:05,208
that expanded
the receiver range.

264
00:12:05,291 --> 00:12:07,625
Way to outdo yourself, Apple!

265
00:12:08,625 --> 00:12:10,416
Okay. There!

266
00:12:13,583 --> 00:12:16,416
[KIRILL]
Zabel. But how?

267
00:12:16,500 --> 00:12:18,666
[DOUG]
I get it now... Zabel.

268
00:12:18,750 --> 00:12:22,000
[ZABEL] Hm? Have you decided
to cooperate, then?

269
00:12:22,083 --> 00:12:23,375
[DOUG]
It's reversed.

270
00:12:23,458 --> 00:12:25,166
The code works backwards.

271
00:12:25,250 --> 00:12:27,166
Reverse alphabetical order.

272
00:12:27,250 --> 00:12:28,666
You've always been the boss.

273
00:12:28,750 --> 00:12:30,916
And what if I have?

274
00:12:31,000 --> 00:12:32,958
[DOUG] Then all I have
to do is take you out

275
00:12:33,041 --> 00:12:35,208
and Esperanza's finished.

276
00:12:36,000 --> 00:12:38,541
[FEMALE THUG 9A]
Boss. Everything's ready to go.

277
00:12:38,625 --> 00:12:39,958
Can't ID the building.

278
00:12:40,041 --> 00:12:42,208
There aren't enough visual
markers to tell much.

279
00:12:42,291 --> 00:12:44,291
Well, if Doug knew,
maybe he could give us

280
00:12:44,375 --> 00:12:45,583
some clues as to
his whereabouts.

281
00:12:45,666 --> 00:12:48,833
Don't worry, he knows
we're watching along.

282
00:12:48,916 --> 00:12:52,041
I modified it,
to deter peeping toms.

283
00:12:52,125 --> 00:12:55,500
[DOUG groans]

284
00:12:55,583 --> 00:12:57,791
[ZABEL]
If you don't talk, you'll die.

285
00:12:57,875 --> 00:12:59,125
But you knew that.

286
00:12:59,208 --> 00:13:01,916
I won't die as easily
as you might think.

287
00:13:02,000 --> 00:13:05,000
'Cause I've finally
found a way forward.

288
00:13:07,708 --> 00:13:08,666
[APPLE]
What is that?

289
00:13:08,750 --> 00:13:10,500
It's a map of
the parking garage.

290
00:13:10,583 --> 00:13:13,041
I'll go run a search for all
garages with that layout.

291
00:13:13,125 --> 00:13:14,583
Come on.

292
00:13:14,666 --> 00:13:16,041
We need to act fast.

293
00:13:16,125 --> 00:13:18,583
Yeah. Doug will never let
these guys break him.

294
00:13:18,666 --> 00:13:20,791
Somehow I could sense that.

295
00:13:20,875 --> 00:13:23,250
He would rather die
than give in!

296
00:13:25,875 --> 00:13:28,375
[ZABEL] Hm... Looks like
he won't be talking,

297
00:13:28,458 --> 00:13:31,125
no matter what atrocities
we subject him to.

298
00:13:31,208 --> 00:13:32,458
Unless something were to happen

299
00:13:32,541 --> 00:13:35,083
that altered his mind
as well as his body.

300
00:13:35,166 --> 00:13:38,541
Perhaps then he'll sing
just like a nightingale.

301
00:13:38,625 --> 00:13:40,041
They're gonna dose
him with Anthem!

302
00:13:40,125 --> 00:13:43,291
Unfortunately, that does seem
to be the plan of attack.

303
00:13:43,375 --> 00:13:45,625
I wish we could tell Doug
what we're up to.

304
00:13:45,708 --> 00:13:47,750
Beyond just letting him know
we're able to watch this.

305
00:13:47,833 --> 00:13:49,541
Wait, I think I
figured something out!

306
00:13:49,625 --> 00:13:51,500
We can send him
whatever message we want!

307
00:13:51,583 --> 00:13:52,875
[GROUP]
Hm?

308
00:13:52,958 --> 00:13:54,916
[ZABEL]
The choice is yours, Billingham.

309
00:13:55,000 --> 00:13:56,708
[THUG 09B]
Uh? What do we do?

310
00:13:56,791 --> 00:13:57,625
[THUG 09A]
I don't wanna...

311
00:13:57,708 --> 00:13:59,125
[KAY]
We can use Morse code.

312
00:13:59,208 --> 00:14:02,916
Doug will notice the on
and off indicator flashing!

313
00:14:07,125 --> 00:14:10,291
[DOUG gasps]
SEVEN-O...

314
00:14:10,375 --> 00:14:11,750
[KIRILL]
What are you telling him?

315
00:14:11,833 --> 00:14:14,083
It's just a simple message
to get his attention.

316
00:14:14,166 --> 00:14:16,791
Hopefully, he'll catch on
fast to what we're doing.

317
00:14:16,875 --> 00:14:18,541
I found out where
they're holding him.

318
00:14:18,625 --> 00:14:21,083
It's the parking structure
on Simpson Drive.

319
00:14:21,166 --> 00:14:24,375
I'll call in a military
special forces unit for back-up.

320
00:14:24,458 --> 00:14:26,833
We'll send in a chopper to
retrieve him from above.

321
00:14:26,916 --> 00:14:28,708
A helicopter's way too risky!

322
00:14:28,791 --> 00:14:31,250
Well, can you think of a faster
way to get to him, then?

323
00:14:31,333 --> 00:14:33,916
[gasps] Doug is using Morse
code to respond!

324
00:14:34,000 --> 00:14:35,166
What? How?

325
00:14:35,250 --> 00:14:36,750
Blinking in rhythm.

326
00:14:36,833 --> 00:14:39,958
He's badly injured
from electric shock, but...

327
00:14:40,041 --> 00:14:41,500
Oh, Doug.

328
00:14:43,416 --> 00:14:44,666
Tell us.

329
00:14:51,041 --> 00:14:53,458
"I'm waiting. Out."

330
00:15:04,250 --> 00:15:06,666
Hey, Boss. I've got an idea.

331
00:15:16,458 --> 00:15:18,500
I approve. Let's do it.

332
00:15:18,583 --> 00:15:19,375
[gasps]

333
00:15:19,458 --> 00:15:21,166
Extralegal measures approved.

334
00:15:21,250 --> 00:15:25,541
The Lisvalletta military shall
assume full responsibility.

335
00:15:25,625 --> 00:15:27,208
Do whatever it takes, team!

336
00:15:27,291 --> 00:15:29,666
Just get out there and
bring Doug back safely!

337
00:15:29,750 --> 00:15:30,833
[ALL]
Roger!

338
00:15:30,916 --> 00:15:32,500
[TRAVIS]
Sophie will continue to monitor

339
00:15:32,583 --> 00:15:34,916
Doug and Buzz-Cuts'
fields of vision.

340
00:15:35,000 --> 00:15:36,083
Buzz-Cut's on the move,

341
00:15:36,166 --> 00:15:38,750
and he'll lead us
to Doug's location.

342
00:15:38,833 --> 00:15:40,000
Pink and Rookie,

343
00:15:40,083 --> 00:15:42,625
you're to provide support
from the rear.

344
00:15:42,708 --> 00:15:45,791
Boxer and Robot,
you'll secure the exit route

345
00:15:45,875 --> 00:15:48,916
so, we can move him out
fast once we've got him.

346
00:15:49,000 --> 00:15:51,541
Buzz-Cut, you're going right
into the belly of the beast

347
00:15:51,625 --> 00:15:54,500
to do whatever you can to
distract the enemy from within.

348
00:15:54,583 --> 00:15:57,666
Then you'll head straight to the
seventh floor and rescue Doug.

349
00:15:57,750 --> 00:16:02,083
We'll call it Operation Beehive!

350
00:16:04,375 --> 00:16:08,125
[TRAVIS]
The team leader is... Buzz-Cut!

351
00:16:08,208 --> 00:16:09,708
[exhales]

352
00:16:09,791 --> 00:16:12,583
[KIRILL] I'll save you,
Doug, no matter what!

353
00:16:12,666 --> 00:16:14,708
The Double Decker system.

354
00:16:14,791 --> 00:16:16,375
It's required of all of you.

355
00:16:16,458 --> 00:16:19,333
You work with a partner at
all times for good reason.

356
00:16:19,416 --> 00:16:21,583
Namely, to keep
your partner alive--

357
00:16:21,666 --> 00:16:24,125
that is your number
one responsibility.

358
00:16:24,208 --> 00:16:26,541
I'm counting on you!

359
00:16:27,333 --> 00:16:30,125
[KIRILL]
Yeah. You can count on me!

360
00:16:30,208 --> 00:16:32,708
Failure is not
an option here, Buzz-Cut.

361
00:16:32,791 --> 00:16:34,208
Are you ready for this?

362
00:16:34,291 --> 00:16:35,458
Don't think, Kirill.

363
00:16:35,541 --> 00:16:37,541
Feel so good. Boo-yah!

364
00:16:37,625 --> 00:16:38,541
[COOPER]
Hm?

365
00:16:38,625 --> 00:16:41,083
It's just a little
good luck charm.

366
00:16:41,166 --> 00:16:42,125
[THUG 09B]
Aw, man.

367
00:16:42,208 --> 00:16:43,625
Is this gonna
kill him, you think?

368
00:16:43,708 --> 00:16:44,500
Guess we'll see.

369
00:16:44,583 --> 00:16:46,041
Hey! C'mon!

370
00:16:46,125 --> 00:16:48,416
If he's not gonna talk,
we don't have a choice!

371
00:16:48,500 --> 00:16:50,666
Yeah, and when he
turns into a monster,

372
00:16:50,750 --> 00:16:52,166
then we can just shoot him dead.

373
00:16:52,250 --> 00:16:53,208
Hold on.

374
00:16:53,291 --> 00:16:55,666
Hm? Have you decided to talk?

375
00:16:55,750 --> 00:16:57,875
[DOUG]
Give me... ten seconds.

376
00:16:57,958 --> 00:16:59,166
--Huh?
--Hm?

377
00:16:59,250 --> 00:17:02,208
Countdown initiated. Nine...

378
00:17:02,291 --> 00:17:03,041
Eight...

379
00:17:03,125 --> 00:17:04,083
Seven...

380
00:17:04,166 --> 00:17:05,041
Six... Five...

381
00:17:05,125 --> 00:17:06,458
--Leave it to me.
--Four...

382
00:17:06,541 --> 00:17:08,541
--Time to stir up the beehive.
--Three... Two...

383
00:17:08,625 --> 00:17:10,375
--Dance for me, little bees!
--One...

384
00:17:10,458 --> 00:17:11,750
Go!

385
00:17:17,583 --> 00:17:18,583
What was that?

386
00:17:18,666 --> 00:17:19,625
[THUGS groaning]

387
00:17:19,708 --> 00:17:20,833
[THUG 09B]
What the hell?!

388
00:17:23,250 --> 00:17:24,000
[THUGS yelp]

389
00:17:24,083 --> 00:17:25,375
A car just exploded?

390
00:17:25,458 --> 00:17:26,375
[THUG 09A]
Shit!

391
00:17:26,458 --> 00:17:27,125
[THUG 09B]
You're comin' with us!

392
00:17:27,208 --> 00:17:29,041
What? No more Anthem?

393
00:17:29,125 --> 00:17:30,375
[THUG 09A]
Just shut up and walk!

394
00:17:30,458 --> 00:17:32,458
Sophie. Where's Doug now?

395
00:17:32,541 --> 00:17:36,291
Kirill. They're taking him
to the top floor!

396
00:17:36,375 --> 00:17:37,208
[KAY]
Confirmed hit!

397
00:17:37,291 --> 00:17:38,500
Right. Kay. Next!

398
00:17:38,583 --> 00:17:40,750
Yes! Location's at six o'clock.

399
00:17:40,833 --> 00:17:41,958
Distance is 180.

400
00:17:42,041 --> 00:17:43,208
Good girl.

401
00:17:43,291 --> 00:17:45,333
I'll give you some
nice doggie treats later.

402
00:17:45,416 --> 00:17:47,125
Just as I thought they would.

403
00:17:47,208 --> 00:17:49,166
The target is
heading up to the roof.

404
00:17:49,250 --> 00:17:51,583
Boxer, Robot, you're up!

405
00:17:51,666 --> 00:17:52,500
[MAXINE, YURI]
Roger!

406
00:17:52,583 --> 00:17:54,500
Kirill, you'd better hurry!

407
00:17:54,583 --> 00:17:56,375
[KIRILL] I can't go
much faster than I am!

408
00:17:56,458 --> 00:17:58,625
[SOPHIE] But the enemy's on
the verge of figuring it out!

409
00:17:58,708 --> 00:18:01,666
Oh! Now the lady's pointing
a gun right at him!

410
00:18:01,750 --> 00:18:03,791
Oh! But now Doug's got the gun!

411
00:18:03,875 --> 00:18:06,416
Oh! Oh! Behind you! Oh!

412
00:18:06,500 --> 00:18:08,666
"Oh," doesn't tell me
a damn thing, Sophie!

413
00:18:08,750 --> 00:18:10,833
Oh! Sorry! Oh!

414
00:18:10,916 --> 00:18:13,416
Uh, um. He just jumped off!

415
00:18:13,500 --> 00:18:14,833
[KIRILL]
Huh?!

416
00:18:14,916 --> 00:18:16,500
[SOPHIE]
Get ready to rendezvous!

417
00:18:16,583 --> 00:18:18,500
"Rendezvous"?!

418
00:18:20,125 --> 00:18:21,166
[gasps]

419
00:18:22,875 --> 00:18:24,666
[DOUG gasping]

420
00:18:27,000 --> 00:18:28,166
Do I have to ride up here?

421
00:18:28,250 --> 00:18:30,625
Just be quiet and stay on me!

422
00:18:35,833 --> 00:18:36,958
[DOUG]
What do we do now?

423
00:18:37,041 --> 00:18:40,583
[KIRILL]
We do... this!

424
00:18:40,666 --> 00:18:43,250
[DOUG grunting]

425
00:18:51,708 --> 00:18:54,666
[KIRILL] Hang on tight now,
Doug! Let's go!

426
00:18:56,208 --> 00:18:59,750
[yells]

427
00:19:02,583 --> 00:19:05,166
[gasping]

428
00:19:05,250 --> 00:19:09,416
[KIRILL]
Hey! Stay still! Damn it!

429
00:19:14,000 --> 00:19:16,041
So close!

430
00:19:16,125 --> 00:19:17,208
[gasping]

431
00:19:19,916 --> 00:19:22,750
I think that this
crazy plan worked. Maybe?

432
00:19:22,833 --> 00:19:26,583
Wow, Kay, you sound
so... confident.

433
00:19:26,666 --> 00:19:27,875
[YURI]
Are you okay down there?

434
00:19:27,958 --> 00:19:29,916
Yeah. I'm all right.

435
00:19:30,000 --> 00:19:32,375
But I don't think
I can move anymore.

436
00:19:32,458 --> 00:19:34,583
You two are model Double
Deckers, you know that?

437
00:19:34,666 --> 00:19:36,166
This looks like a Triple Decker.

438
00:19:36,250 --> 00:19:39,000
Hey! Not everyone
can breathe right now!

439
00:19:39,083 --> 00:19:41,208
[DOUG] Not much longer.
You've got this.

440
00:19:41,291 --> 00:19:46,166
[KIRILL] What if I die
before we get there?!

441
00:19:47,750 --> 00:19:50,166
[KAY] Mr. Dorman confessed
to his involvement.

442
00:19:50,250 --> 00:19:52,833
He thought being a hero would
help him win the election.

443
00:19:52,916 --> 00:19:54,041
His genius idea

444
00:19:54,125 --> 00:19:55,333
was to stage
the fake kidnapping

445
00:19:55,416 --> 00:19:57,708
so he would come out
looking like a rock star.

446
00:19:57,791 --> 00:20:00,458
[TRAVIS] Yep. I figured it was
something along those lines.

447
00:20:00,541 --> 00:20:01,458
So, uh.

448
00:20:01,541 --> 00:20:03,375
We caused lots of
property damage.

449
00:20:03,458 --> 00:20:04,833
Are we gonna have
to answer for that?

450
00:20:04,916 --> 00:20:07,000
Of course not. Trust me.

451
00:20:07,083 --> 00:20:08,583
Leave it to yours truly.

452
00:20:08,666 --> 00:20:11,208
Travis, you're so cool!

453
00:20:12,083 --> 00:20:13,666
[TRAVIS]
The Lisvalletta military

454
00:20:13,750 --> 00:20:16,750
shall assume full
responsibility!

455
00:20:16,833 --> 00:20:19,125
Whelp. I guess
it all worked out.

456
00:20:19,208 --> 00:20:21,375
Hey, uh. I was a big
help, you guys.

457
00:20:21,458 --> 00:20:24,666
Yeah. You did stellar
work... Doctor Apple.

458
00:20:24,750 --> 00:20:27,541
Dammit, call me Doctor A--

459
00:20:27,625 --> 00:20:30,666
But now, will you please
take off that view jack crap?

460
00:20:30,750 --> 00:20:35,041
Just because it came in handy
this time doesn't make it okay!

461
00:20:35,125 --> 00:20:37,291
Fine. I'll take it off.

462
00:20:37,375 --> 00:20:40,625
Wait. Is Kirill coming into
the office today, or what?

463
00:20:40,708 --> 00:20:43,375
[MAXINE] Nah, he's off.
He went to visit Doug.

464
00:20:43,458 --> 00:20:45,583
[KIRILL] "You don't need
to thank me, buddy.

465
00:20:45,666 --> 00:20:47,833
I just did what any
partner would've."

466
00:20:47,916 --> 00:20:49,208
Yep. That's right.

467
00:20:49,291 --> 00:20:51,958
Gotta look out for
your Double Decker.

468
00:20:52,041 --> 00:20:53,125
Uh!

469
00:20:55,458 --> 00:20:57,125
Ah. Hello, there.

470
00:20:57,208 --> 00:21:00,375
I dropped by to offer Sergeant
Billingham an apology.

471
00:21:00,458 --> 00:21:01,625
I put his life in jeopardy,

472
00:21:01,708 --> 00:21:03,833
and I want him to know
I'll never forget that.

473
00:21:03,916 --> 00:21:06,166
You're kind, but Doug would
never think twice about it.

474
00:21:06,250 --> 00:21:09,041
[COOPER] I'm impressed with
how brave you all are.

475
00:21:09,125 --> 00:21:11,291
Nah. I'm nothing special.

476
00:21:11,375 --> 00:21:13,000
Heh. Bye!

477
00:21:15,333 --> 00:21:16,458
By the way.

478
00:21:16,541 --> 00:21:18,583
That little good luck
charm of yours.

479
00:21:18,666 --> 00:21:20,416
Where did you say
you heard it, again?

480
00:21:20,500 --> 00:21:21,833
Huh?

481
00:21:21,916 --> 00:21:25,166
[COOPER] "Don't think.
Feel so good." Wasn't that it?

482
00:21:25,250 --> 00:21:26,875
Oh. That. Right.

483
00:21:26,958 --> 00:21:28,625
It's just a little motto
my grandfather

484
00:21:28,708 --> 00:21:30,416
taught me before
he passed away.

485
00:21:30,500 --> 00:21:33,250
Though, to be honest, I'm not
sure those are the exact words.

486
00:21:33,333 --> 00:21:34,583
I forget.

487
00:21:34,666 --> 00:21:37,083
I see. Well,
it's still good advice.

488
00:21:37,166 --> 00:21:39,708
My grandpa would've
loved to hear you say that.

489
00:21:39,791 --> 00:21:40,583
See ya, sir!

490
00:21:40,666 --> 00:21:42,500
[door creaks]

491
00:21:44,541 --> 00:21:46,833
[DOUG]
Thank you, Constable Vrubel.

492
00:21:46,916 --> 00:21:48,416
You don't need to
thank me, buddy.

493
00:21:48,500 --> 00:21:49,333
I just did what any par--

494
00:21:49,416 --> 00:21:51,208
You're officially my hero now.

495
00:21:51,291 --> 00:21:53,166
[KIRILL gasping]

496
00:21:53,250 --> 00:21:54,541
If the roles had been reversed,

497
00:21:54,625 --> 00:21:56,708
I'm not so sure I would have
done the same for you.

498
00:21:56,791 --> 00:21:58,625
So, I feel especially grateful.

499
00:21:58,708 --> 00:22:01,125
[KIRILL]
Huh?

500
00:22:01,208 --> 00:22:03,833
